     * [120]Gary B
       a buffer is just a pre-allocated area of memory where you store
       your data while you're processing it. Since YOU define the buffer
       in code, "what kind" of buffer is not a question. It is "whatever
       kind" that you decide to make it, by the way your code is written.
       Any time you read from a disk you read into a buffer. Your read
       routine probably has provision for a pointer to an area of memory
       the data will be stored in AFTER it is read. This IS your buffer.
       The trouble is, many compilers don't allow for more than 32000
       bytes of buffer space (some 65000). I hope you "2*650000" is a
       typo! That is HUGE! You need to develope an algorithm that will
       divide this up into smaller "chunks" that your compiler can handle.
       [121]Gary B ¬∑ 7 years ago
